## Example 3 — Rate of Change Calculation

A table shows the temperature each hour:

| Time (hours) | Temperature (°F) |
|--------------|------------------|
| 6 | 45 |
| 8 | 55 |
| 10 | 65 |
| 12 | 70 |
| 14 | 68 |

Find the rate of change from hour 6 to hour 10 and from hour 12 to hour 14.

### Step 1: Rate of Change from Hour 6 to Hour 10

$$\text{Rate} = \frac{65 - 45}{10 - 6} = \frac{20}{4} = 5 \text{ °F per hour}$$

### Step 2: Rate of Change from Hour 12 to Hour 14

$$\text{Rate} = \frac{68 - 70}{14 - 12} = \frac{-2}{2} = -1 \text{ °F per hour}$$

### Step 3: Interpret

From hour 6 to 10, the temperature rose at 5°F per hour. From hour 12 to 14, it dropped at 1°F per hour.

### Step 4: Is This Linear?

The rate of change is not constant (5 vs. $-1$). This data is **not linear** — the temperature rises, peaks, then falls.

✅ Answer: Rate from 6–10 hours = 5°F/hr (warming). Rate from 12–14 hours = $-1$°F/hr (cooling). **Nonlinear.**

